1 (7) Other factors the Department considers appropriate.
2 (c) The Department may not establish or impose a fee on coal combustion
3 by–products that are:
4 (1) Beneficially used, as the Department determines; or
5 (2) Used for coal mine reclamation in accordance with regulations the
6 Department adopts or with regulations of the receiving state.
7 (d) Fees imposed on coal combustion by–products that are transported for use or
8 disposal out–of–state may not exceed 50% of the fees established for disposal in–State.
9 (e) The fees collected by the Department under this section shall be deposited into
10 the Fund and used in accordance with § 9–284 of this subtitle.
11 (f) The fees imposed shall be set at the rate necessary to implement the purposes
12 set forth in § 9–284 of this subtitle.
13 (g) In any fiscal year, if the fee schedule established by the Department generates
14 revenue that exceeds the amount necessary to operate a regulatory program to control the
15 management of coal combustion by–products, the Department shall reduce the fees in the
16 following fiscal year USE THE EXCESS REVENUE TO TAKE ACTION NECESSARY TO:
17 (1) INCREASE THE BENEFICIAL REUSE OF COAL COMBUSTION
18 BY–PRODUCTS; AND
19 (2) MITIGATE HUMAN HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACTS DUE
20 TO THE RELEASE OF COAL COMBUSTION BY–PRODUCTS FROM PRIORITY SITES.
21 9–291.
22 (A) IN THIS SECTION, “COORDINATING COMMITTEE” MEANS THE
23 STATEWIDE COAL COMBUSTION BY–PRODUCTS COORDINATING COMMITTEE.
24 (B) THERE IS A STATEWIDE COAL COMBUSTION BY–PRODUCTS
25 COORDINATING COMMITTEE.
26 (C) THE COORDINATING COMMITTEE CONSISTS OF THE FOLLOWING
27 MEMBERS:
28 (1) THE SECRETARY, OR THE SECRETARY’S DESIGNEE;
29 (2) ONE REPRESENTATIVE OF THE COMMISSION ON
30 ENVIRONMENTAL JUSTICE AND SUSTAINABLE COMMUNITIES;

